[3] United Kingdom (Wales)
Date: Thu 7 Nov 2013
Source: BBC Wales [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-south-west-wales-24854277


The latest outbreak comes less than 4 months after Wales' biggest measles outbreak. Public Health Wales (PHW) renewed its call for parents to urgently get their children vaccinated to stop the disease from spreading. PHW said it was "very frustrated" with cases reaching 36 since early October 2013. The latest outbreak comes less than 4 months after Wales' biggest measles outbreak ended, centred on the same area with 1200 suspected cases.

The outbreak has affected 4 schools in the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board (ABM) area. "Parents and young people should not underestimate how serious measles can be and how quickly it can spread," said Dr Jorg Hoffmann, consultant in communicable disease control for PHW. "In a school setting, one child with measles sitting in a classroom for just one hour will lead to at least 70 per cent of other pupils who are not vaccinated catching measles. PHW is working closely with ABM to bring the outbreak under control, and where a sufficient number of children are unvaccinated in a school where there have been measles cases, school vaccination sessions will be arranged.

The Swansea area epidemic lasted 8 months with suspected cases 1st reported in November 2012. By the time the outbreak was declared over in July 2013, it had resulted in 1219 notifications of measles cases in the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg, Hywel Dda and Powys health board areas. Some 88 people visited a hospital due to measles during the outbreak, and more than 75 000 were vaccinated throughout Wales. A 25-year-old male from Swansea died from pneumonia after contracting the virus at the height of the epidemic.

Although more than 70 000 catch up doses of MMR were given across Wales during the outbreak, around 30 000 children and young people in the 10 to 18 age group remain unprotected. Dr Hoffmann added: "We are very frustrated to see more cases of measles in the area so soon after the large outbreak earlier this year [2013], and we are very keen for this to be stopped before it can get any bigger and we return to a position where children are admitted to hospital or die or are damaged by the disease. The only way to achieve that is through vaccination, and I urge parents whose children have not received 2 doses of MMR to ensure that they speak to their GP immediately to arrange this quick, safe and effective vaccine."

--
