[6] Brazil (multi-province) - Alert
Date: Thu 7 Nov 2013
Source: 6 Digital [in Spanish, machine trans. edited]
http://www.noticiasdel6.com/ampliar_.php?id=122688


The Ministry of Health, through the Department of Epidemiology has reported the occurrence of a measles outbreak in Brazil involving the States of Pernambuco, Sao Paulo, Minas Gerais, Santa Catarina, Paraiba and Distrito Federal. The Provincial Health Portfolio advised that those who are traveling to neighbouring administrations should obtain rubella and measles immunisation before travelling to and entering border areas (i.e. Puerto Iguazu, San Antonio, Bernardo de Irigoyen, San Pedro, The Proud, Alba Posse and San Javier).

It also recommended that people should in any case verify their vaccination status in relation to their age and the national requirements: i.e. children 13 months to 5 years must have received one dose of MMR [measles, mumps and rubella] vaccine, and persons aged 6-50 years should have received at least have 2 doses of a vaccine containing at least 2 of the 3 MMWR components (measles and rubella), and have documentary evidence to confirm their status, or alternatively accredited serology (IgG) for rubella and measles. People over 50 are considered to be immune (as a consequence of previous exposure to the infection prior to the availability of vaccine).

When there is doubt about vaccination status, it is recommended that people obtain vaccination at least 10 days before travelling.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the Pan-American Health Organisation (PAHO), globally, measles remains a leading cause of death in young children, claiming an estimated 380 lives every day, or 15 every hour (WHO data, 2010). In 2002, the Americas became the 1st WHO region to interrupt endemic measles transmission. Between 2003 and 2010, annual notified measles cases averaged 156 per year, virtually all imported or related to importations. In 2011, the number of measles cases in the region jumped to 1324, due to importation of viruses from several large outbreaks occurring in Europe and Africa. 93 percent of all cases in the Americas in 2011 were reported from 3 countries: Canada, Ecuador and the United States http://www.paho.org/hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_view&gid=19670&Itemid=.

The 1st case of measles in Brazil in the past 10 years was recorded on 21 Jan this year [2013]. Since then, a total of 114 cases of measles have been confirmed, 98 of them in Pernambuco, 7 in Paraiba, 5 in Sao Paulo, 2 in Mato Grosso, one in Santa Catarina, and one in the Federal District. Travellers to Brazil must ensure that they have been adequately immunised with the mumps-measles-rubella [MMR] vaccine. Immunity is assumed for those born before 1966, but for all others, a clear history of the disease, evidence of 2 vaccinations with MMR or a positive blood test are advisable, but, if in doubt, a single MMR vaccination a fortnight prior to travel should provide sufficient protection (From: http://www.traveldoctor.com.au/Article/Alerts/South-America/Measles-in-Brazil. - Mod.CP

A ProMED-mail HealthMap can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1zJi.]

