[9] Canada (Saskatchewan)
Date: Thu 7 Nov 2013
Source: The Globe and Mail [abridged & edited]
http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/suspected-measles-case-in-saskatchewan-worries-health-officials/article15330274/


Saskatchewan's 1st suspected case of measles is not being linked to an outbreak in southern Alberta, but that has not left Saskatchewan health officials breathing any easier. With Regina preparing for several high-profile events, including the 101st Grey Cup game, Saqib Shahab, the province's chief medical officer, acknowledged "a suspected" case of measles had been reported with "some history of travel to southern Alberta." But Dr. Shahab was quick to add: "This case is not currently considered linked to the Alberta outbreak. The symptoms were mild, and the patient is fully recovered. ... Even so, we still have to raise awareness."

Given how far and how quickly the contagious disease can spread, Saskatchewan went on alert not long after Alberta Health Services reported its 1st case in late October, a Grade 9 student at the Coaldale Christian School. Southern Alberta has low immunization rates, and so far, 20 cases have been confirmed in the Lethbridge area.

Saskatchewan health officials took to reminding people that measles has not been eradicated and that vaccinations and booster shots are a necessary defence. "We are fairly close in proximity [to southern Alberta], and there are lots of cultural ties, family ties and business reasons for people to go back and forth," said Dr. Shahab, who is based in Regina. "The last 3 years, we've been increasingly aware of measles. Last year [2012], we had 2 cases in Regina in the spring and 4 cases in the fall. In Saskatoon and Prince Albert, we had 2 cases. So in recent years, we had 8 cases, and we did a lot to boost immunization rates."

Saskatchewan's immunization rate is 92 per cent for 2 doses of the measles vaccine. In Alberta, the rate sits at 85 per cent, well off the stated goal of 98 per cent to achieve what is known as herd immunity. Immunization is not mandatory in either province, yet both set up vaccination clinics and assessment centres. In Regina, staying measles free is about to become a necessity.

[Byline: Allan Maki]

--
