[10] USA (Michigan)
Date: Tue 5 Nov 2013
Source: Battle Creek enquirer.com [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.battlecreekenquirer.com/article/20131105/NEWS01/311050015/State-confirms-rare-measles-case-here-earlier-year


A new report shows an increase in the rates of certain infectious diseases in Michigan, including a case of measles in Calhoun County. The Michigan Department of Community Health issues a weekly report of the Michigan Disease Surveillance System. For the 2 Nov 2013 report, one case of measles was reported for Calhoun County. Health Officer Jim Rutherford of the Calhoun County Public Health Department said it was the 1st he's seen here in more than 5 years.

The measles case, an 8-month-old child, contracted the disease while in Pakistan earlier this year [2013]. The health department then suspected measles, but final testing was yet to come, officials said in May 2013. The MDCH report has confirmed it. The health department followed up by finding out who came into contact with the child in this area and worked with officials in Kalamazoo County as well.

Measles is a highly contagious respiratory virus. People of any age can get it, although the measles-mumps-rubella vaccine is effective against it. Children between 6 months and one year old can get the vaccine, Rutherford said. The MMR vaccine is required for school attendance in Michigan. The disease can be mild in children but dangerous to pregnant women; congenital rubella syndrome affects the fetus and can lead to health problems later in life.

The Calhoun case is one of 5 in the state so far this year [2013]. Three cases were in Midland County, and another one happened in Kent County. None were reported statewide in 2009 or 2010, 2 in 2011, and one in 2012.

--
