[11] Australia (SA)
Date: Thu 7 Nov 2013
Source: The Australian [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/2nd-case-of-measles-reported-in-south-australian-woman-who-visited-bali/story-e6frg6n6-1226755090669


The latest [measles] case is a 36-year-old woman but is not linked to the 6 children aged 7-14 reported yesterday [6 Nov 2013] who caught the disease while holidaying in Bali. South Australia [SA] Health has issued another public health alert after confirmation that the woman has the highly infectious disease. SA Health Chief Medical Officer, Professor Paddy Phillips said the woman is in a stable condition in hospital.

"While measles is not very common in Australia anymore, it is still widespread in other parts of the world, such as South East Asia and Europe," Professor Phillips said. "This case of measles was acquired in Bali, which is a very popular holiday destination at this time of year for schoolies and summer holidays. "If you are considering travelling overseas, it is important to remember to make sure all your vaccinations are up to date."

SA Health has contacted a number of other people known to have been exposed to the cases during the infectious period. "We are advising everyone, especially people who were in the locations mentioned during these times, to be alert for symptoms," Professor Phillips said. "The illness begins with fever, cough, runny nose, and sore eyes, followed by a rash which begins on the head and then spreads down the body. Complications of measles can be severe.

An alert has been issued to General Practitioners advising them of this case.

This is the 10th case of measles reported in South Australia during 2013, compared to 3 cases at this time last year [2012]. A total of 6 cases were recorded in 2012.

Contact points with the children who fell ill include the Adelaide Hills Farmers Market at Mt Barker on 12 Oct 2013, the Morphettville Medical Centre at Glenelg East on 13 Oct 2013, Kirinari Community School at Unley on 15-16 Oct 2013, and the Plympton Family Practice on 16 Oct 2013.

[Byline: Brad Crouch]

